<biogHist>
<abstract>The Sydney Foundling Hospital was established in Port View House, Stewart Street, Paddington in 1875. Previously, it was known as the Sydney Foundling Institution and had been located in Darlinghurst from 1874 to 1875. In 1877 the institution moved again and became The Infants' Home, Ashfield.</abstract>
<p>A newspaper article from 1878 (by which time the Sydney Foundling Hospital had moved from Paddington to Ashfield, and been renamed The Infants' Home) contains information about the first years of this institution.</p>
<p>The article mentioned that the original hospital, the Sydney Foundling Institution in Darlinghurst (1874 to 1875) 'did not prove so successful in that quarter as was anticipated, although well marshalled by the elite of Sydney female society'. After moving to Paddington in 1875 and changing its name, the institution reportedly 'met with no better success â€¦ in fact, the institution was languishing for a want of more little ones', according to the article in the <span style="font-style:italic">Australian Town and Country Journal</span> published in May 1878. The article provided these figures about the activities of the Sydney Foundling Hospital between June 1875 and June 1876:</p>
<p>'In the hospital, 15; left at the door, or in places continuous to the hospital, 14; admitted on the application of their mothers, 14, and admitted with their mothers, 12; total, 55. This number is disposed of as follows: Deaths, 24; adopted by well-to-do respectable childless couples, 3; left with their mothers, 9; and present in the institution on June 1, 1876, 21: total 55.'</p>
<p>The article went on to state that the institution, since its move to Ashfield in 1877, 'now thrives'.</p>
